e inventor of the Elo rating system</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>Elo<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> rating syst=
em</b> is a method for calculating the relative skill levels of players in =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-sum_game" title=3D"Zero-sum g=
ame">zero-sum games</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch=
ess" title=3D"Chess">chess</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Esports" title=3D"Esports">esports</a>. It is named after its creator <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arpad_Elo" title=3D"Arpad Elo">Arpad El=
o</a>, a Hungarian-American <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_=
master" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chess master">chess master</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics<=
/a> professor. The Elo system was invented as an improved <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_rating_system" title=3D"Chess rating system">=
chess rating system</a> over the previously used <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Harkness_rating_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Harkn=
ess rating system">Harkness rating system</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-aodhostin=
g_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rat=
ing_system#cite_note-aodhosting-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but it is also used as a rati=
ng system in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_football"=
 title=3D"Association football">association football</a> (soccer), <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_football" title=3D"American foot=
ball">American football</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseb=
all" title=3D"Baseball">baseball</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Basketball" title=3D"Basketball">basketball</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pool_(cue_sports)" title=3D"Pool (cue sports)">pool</a>,=
 various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Board_game" title=3D"Boar=
d game">board games</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esport=
s" title=3D"Esports">esports</a>, and more recently <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Large_language_model" title=3D"Large language model">larg=
e language models</a>.
</p><p>The difference in the ratings between two players serves as a predic=
tor of the outcome of a match. Two players with equal ratings who play agai=
nst each other are expected to score an equal number of wins. A player whos=
e rating is 100 points greater than their opponent's is expected to score 6=
4%; if the difference is 200 points, then the expected score for the strong=
er player is 76%.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A player's Elo rating is a number that may change depending on the o=
utcome of rated games played. After every game, the winning player takes po=
ints from the losing one. The difference between the ratings of the winner =
and loser determines the total number of points gained or lost after a game=
. If the higher-rated player wins, only a few rating points (or even a frac=
tion of a rating point) will be taken from the lower-rated player; however,=
 if the lower-rated player scores an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Upset_(competition)" title=3D"Upset (competition)">upset win</a>, many r=
ating points will be transferred. The lower-rated player will also gain a f=
ew points from the higher-rated player in the event of a draw. This means t=
hat this rating system is self-correcting. In the long run, players whose r=
atings are too low or too high should do better or worse, respectively, tha=
n the rating system predicts and thus gain or lose rating points until the =
ratings reflect their true playing strength.
</p><p>Elo ratings are comparative only and are valid only within the ratin=
g pool in which they were calculated, rather than being an absolute measure=
 of a player's strength. While Elo-like systems are widely used in two-play=
er settings, variations have also been applied to multiplayer competitions.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElo_rating_system&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arpad_Elo" title=3D"Arpad Elo">=
Arpad Elo</a> was a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_master" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chess master">chess master</a> and an active=
 participant in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_=
Chess_Federation" title=3D"United States Chess Federation">United States Ch=
ess Federation</a> (USCF) from its founding in 1939.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_sys=
tem#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The USCF used a numerical ratings system devise=
d by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenneth_Harkness" title=3D"Ke=
nneth Harkness">Kenneth Harkness</a> to enable members to track their indiv=
idual progress in terms other than tournament wins and losses. The Harkness=
 system was reasonably fair,<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D=
"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_attribution=
s" title=3D"Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span title=3D"The ma=
terial near this tag may use weasel words or too-vague attribution. (June 2=
025)">according to whom?</span></a></i>]</sup> but in some circumstances ga=
ve rise to ratings many observers considered inaccurate. On behalf of the U=
SCF, Elo devised a new system with a more sound<sup class=3D"noprint Inline=
-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:=
Please clarify"><span title=3D"The text near this tag may need clarificatio=
n or removal of jargon. (August 2024)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]=
</sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statis=
tics">statistical</a> basis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-6"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> At about the same time, Gy=C3=B6rgy Karoly and Roger Cook independently=
 developed a system based on the same principles for the New South Wales Ch=
ess Association.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Elo's system replaced earlier systems of competitive rewards with on=
e based on statistical estimation. Rating systems for many sports award poi=
nts in accordance with subjective evaluations of the 'greatness' of certain=
 achievements. For example, winning an important <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Golf" title=3D"Golf">golf</a> tournament might be worth an a=
rbitrarily chosen five times as many points as winning a lesser tournament.=
 A statistical endeavor, by contrast, uses a model that relates the game re=
sults to underlying variables representing the ability of each player.
</p><p>Elo's central assumption was that the chess performance of each play=
er in each game is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distri=
bution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normally distributed</a> <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">ran=
dom variable</a>. Although a player might perform significantly better or w=
orse from one game to the next, Elo assumed that the mean value of the perf=
ormances of any given player changes only slowly over time. Elo thought of =
a player's true skill as the mean of that player's performance random varia=
ble. A further assumption is necessary because chess performance in the abo=
ve sense is still not measurable. One cannot look at a sequence of moves an=
d derive a number to represent that player's skill. Performance can only be=
 inferred from wins, draws, and losses. Therefore, a player who wins a game=
 is assumed to have performed at a higher level than the opponent for that =
game. Conversely, a losing player is assumed to have performed at a lower l=
evel. If the game ends in  a draw, the two players are assumed to have perf=
ormed at nearly the same level.
</p><p>Elo did not specify exactly how close two performances ought to be t=
o result in a draw as opposed to a win or loss. Actually, there is a probab=
ility of a draw that is dependent on the performance differential, so this =
latter is more of a confidence interval than any deterministic frontier. An=
d while he thought it was likely that players might have different <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" title=3D"Standard dev=
iation">standard deviations</a> to their performances, he made a simplifyin=
g assumption to the contrary. To simplify computation even further, Elo pro=
posed a straightforward method of estimating the variables in his model (i.=
e., the true skill of each player). One could calculate relatively easily f=
rom tables how many games players would be expected to win based on compari=
sons of their ratings to those of their opponents. The ratings of a player =
who won more games than expected would be adjusted upward, while those of a=
 player who won fewer than expected would be adjusted downward. Moreover, t=
hat adjustment was to be in linear proportion to the number of wins by whic=
h the player had exceeded or fallen short of their expected number.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>From a modern perspective, Elo's simplifying assumptions are not nec=
essary because computing power is inexpensive and widely available. Several=
 people, most notably <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Glickma=
n" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mark Glickman">Mark Glickman</a>, have pr=
oposed using more sophisticated statistical machinery to estimate the same =
variables. On the other hand, the computational simplicity of the Elo syste=
m has proven to be one of its greatest assets. With the aid of a pocket cal=
culator, an informed chess competitor can calculate to within one point wha=
t their next officially published rating will be, which helps promote a per=
ception that the ratings are fair.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Implementing_Elo's_scheme">=
<span id=3D"Implementing_Elo.27s_scheme"></span>Implementing Elo's scheme</=
h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[<=
/span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElo_rating_sy=
stem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Implementing=
 Elo's scheme"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>The USCF implemented Elo's suggestions in 1960,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-about=
USCF_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_=
rating_system#cite_note-aboutUSCF-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the system quickly gain=
ed recognition as being both fairer and more accurate than the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_rating_systems#Harkness_system" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chess rating systems">Harkness rating system</a>. El=
o's system was adopted by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3=
%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_des_%C3%89checs" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"F=C3=A9d=C3=A9ration Internationale des =C3=89checs">World Chess Feder=
ation</a> (FIDE) in 1970.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-10"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Elo described his work in detail in <i>The Rating of Chessplayers, Past =
and Present</i>, first published in 1978.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AEE1986_11-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_sys=
tem#cite_note-AEE1986-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Subsequent statistical tests have suggested that chess performance i=
s almost certainly not distributed as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distributio=
n</a>, as weaker players have greater winning chances than Elo's model pred=
icts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rat=
ing_system#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In paired comparison data, there is of=
ten very little practical difference in whether it is assumed that the diff=
erences in players' strengths are normally or <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Logistic_distribution" title=3D"Logistic distribution">logistic=
ally</a> distributed. Mathematically, however, the logistic function is mor=
e convenient to work with than the normal distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating=
_system#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
FIDE continues to use the rating difference table as proposed by Elo.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-fiderr2017_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-fiderr2017-15"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Location: table 8.1b">:=E2=80=8A=
table 8.1b=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The development of the Percentage Expectancy Table (table 2.11) is d=
escribed in more detail by Elo as follows:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_=
note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The normal probabilities may be taken directly from the standard
tables of the areas under the normal curve when the difference in rating is
expressed as a z score. Since the standard deviation =CF=83 of individual
performances is defined as 200 points, the standard deviation =CF=83' of th=
e
differences in performances becomes =CF=83=E2=88=9A2 or 282.84. The z value=
 of a
difference then is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i> / 282.84</span>. This w=
ill then divide the area under the
curve into two parts, the larger giving P for the higher rated player and
the smaller giving P for the lower rated player.
</p><p>For example, let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i> =3D 160</span>. Th=
en <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>z</i> =3D 160 / 282.84 =3D .566</span>. The t=
able
gives <span class=3D"texhtml">.7143</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">.285=
7</span> as the areas of the two portions under the curve.
These probabilities are rounded to two figures in table 2.11.
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The table is actually built with standard deviation <span class=3D"texht=
ml">200(10/7)</span> as an approximation for <span class=3D"texhtml">200=E2=
=88=9A2</span>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2023)">citation need=
ed</span></a></i>]</sup> The normal and logistic distributions are in a way=
 arbitrary points in a spectrum of distributions which would work well. In =
practice, both of these distributions work very well for a number of differ=
ent games.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"whi=
te-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Ci=
tation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This clai=
m needs references to reliable sources. (August 2024)">citation needed</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Different_ratings_systems">=
Different ratings systems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D=
"Edit section: Different ratings systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The phrase "Elo rating" is often used to mean a player's chess rating as=
 calculated by FIDE. However, this usage may be confusing or misleading bec=
ause Elo's general ideas have been adopted by many organizations, including=
 the USCF (before FIDE), many other national chess federations, the short-l=
ived <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Professional_Chess_Associatio=
n" title=3D"Professional Chess Association">Professional Chess Association<=
/a> (PCA), and online chess servers including the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Chess_Club" title=3D"Internet Chess Club">Internet=
 Chess Club</a> (ICC), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_Intern=
et_Chess_Server" title=3D"Free Internet Chess Server">Free Internet Chess S=
erver</a> (FICS), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lichess" title=
=3D"Lichess">Lichess</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess.co=
m" title=3D"Chess.com">Chess.com</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Yahoo_Games" title=3D"Yahoo Games">Yahoo! Games</a>. Each organizat=
ion has a unique implementation, and none of them follow Elo's original sug=
gestions precisely.
</p><p>Instead one may refer to the organization granting the rating. For e=
xample: "As of April 2018, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tatev_A=
brahamyan" title=3D"Tatev Abrahamyan">Tatev Abrahamyan</a> had a FIDE ratin=
g of 2366 and a USCF rating of 2473." The Elo ratings of these various orga=
nizations are not directly comparable, since Elo ratings measure the result=
s within a closed pool of players rather than absolute skill.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"FIDE_ratings">FIDE ratings<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElo_rating_s=
ystem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: FIDE rating=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIDE_rankings" title=3D"FIDE ranking=
s">FIDE rankings</a></div> <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote=
 navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/List_of_FIDE_chess_world_number_ones" title=3D"List of FIDE chess world=
 number ones">List of FIDE chess world number ones</a></div>
<p>For top players, the most important rating is their <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIDE" title=3D"FIDE">FIDE</a> rating. FIDE has issued =
the following lists:
</p>
<ul><li>From 1971 to 1980, one list a year was issued.</li>
<li>From 1981 to 2000, two lists a year were issued, in January and July.</=
li>
<li>From July 2000 to July 2009, four lists a year were issued, at the star=
t of January, April, July and October.</li>
<li>From July 2009 to July 2012, six lists a year were issued, at the start=
 of January, March, May, July, September and November.</li>
<li>Since July 2012, the list has been updated monthly.</li></ul>
<p>The following analysis of the July 2015 FIDE rating list gives a rough i=
mpression of what a given FIDE rating means in terms of world ranking:
</p>
<ul><li>5,323 players had an active rating in the range 2200 to 2299, which=
 is usually associated with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
ndidate_Master" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Candidate Master">Candidate =
Master</a> title.</li>
<li>2,869 players had an active rating in the range 2300 to 2399, which is =
usually associated with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIDE_M=
aster" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"FIDE Master">FIDE Master</a> title.</=
li>
<li>1,420 players had an active rating between 2400 and 2499, most of whom =
had either the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Maste=
r" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Master">International Maste=
r</a> or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Grandma=
ster" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Grandmaster">Internation=
al Grandmaster</a> title.</li>
<li>542 players had an active rating between 2500 and 2599, most of whom ha=
d the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Grandmaster" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Grandmaster">International Gran=
dmaster</a> title.</li>
<li>187 players had an active rating between 2600 and 2699, all of whom had=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Grandmaster" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Grandmaster">International Grand=
master</a> title.</li>
<li>40 players had an active rating between 2700 and 2799.</li>
<li>4 players had an active rating of over 2800. (<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Magnus_Carlsen" title=3D"Magnus Carlsen">Magnus Carlsen</a>=
 was rated 2853, and 3 players were rated between 2814 and 2816).</li></ul>
<p>The highest ever FIDE rating was 2882, which <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Magnus_Carlsen" title=3D"Magnus Carlsen">Magnus Carlsen</a> h=
ad on the May 2014 list. A list of the highest-rated players ever is at <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_top_chess_players_throu=
ghout_history" title=3D"Comparison of top chess players throughout history"=
>Comparison of top chess players throughout history</a>.
</p>
