      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>N</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>W</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle N_{W}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/26f1e01a3126cb2520c2081cde320a052225108f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:3.82ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle N_{W=
}}"></span> is the number of rated games won, <span class=3D"mwe-math-eleme=
nt mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-=
mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998=
/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle N_{D}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>N</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>D</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle N_{D}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ba9442fc4e7b77d2ca78d9ac8f7e86472bcc54fc" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:3.459ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle N_{=
D}}"></span> is the number of rated games drawn, and <span class=3D"mwe-mat=
h-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mw=
e-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.o=
rg/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle N_{R}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>N</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>R</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle N_{R}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/89c4ec86a9e1eba4707b587b5288ac7687ce4d64" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:3.346ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle N_{=
R}}"></span> is the number of events in which the player completed three or=
 more rated games.
</p><p>Higher rating floors exist for experienced players who have achieved=
 significant ratings. Such higher rating floors exist, starting at ratings =
of 1200 in 100-point increments up to 2100 (1200, 1300, 1400, ..., 2100). A=
 rating floor is calculated by taking the player's peak established rating,=
 subtracting 200 points, and then rounding down to the nearest rating floor=
. For example, a player who has reached a peak rating of 1464 would have a =
rating floor of <span class=3D"texhtml">1464 =E2=88=92 200 =3D 1264</span>,=
 which would be rounded down to 1200. Under this scheme, only Class C playe=
rs and above are capable of having a higher rating floor than their absolut=
e player rating. All other players would have a floor of at most 150.
</p><p>There are two ways to achieve higher rating floors other than under =
the standard scheme presented above. If a player has achieved the rating of=
 Original Life Master, their rating floor is set at 2200. The achievement o=
f this title is unique in that no other recognized USCF title will result i=
n a new floor. For players with ratings below 2000, winning a cash prize of=
 $2,000 or more raises that player's rating floor to the closest 100-point =
level that would have disqualified the player for participation in the tour=
nament. For example, if a player won $4,000 in a 1750-and-under tournament,=
 they would now have a rating floor of 1800.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Theory">Theory</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElo_rating_system&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Theory"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pairwise_comparison_(psychology=
)" title=3D"Pairwise comparison (psychology)">Pairwise comparisons</a> form=
 the basis of the Elo rating methodology.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_n=
ote-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Elo made references to the papers of Good,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo=
_rating_system#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> David,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#=
cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Trawinski and David,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#c=
ite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> and Buhlman and Huber.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#=
cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mathematical_details">Mathe=
matical details</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Mathematical details"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Performance is not measured absolutely; it is inferred from wins, losses=
, and draws against other players. Players' ratings depend on the ratings o=
f their opponents and the results scored against them. The difference in ra=
ting between two players determines an estimate for the expected score betw=
een them. Both the average and the spread of ratings can be arbitrarily cho=
sen. The USCF initially aimed for an average club player to have a rating o=
f 1500 and Elo suggested scaling ratings so that a difference of 200 rating=
 points in chess would mean that the stronger player has an <i>expected sco=
re</i> of approximately 0.75.
</p><p>A player's <i>expected score</i> is their probability of winning plu=
s half their probability of drawing. Thus, an expected score of 0.75 could =
represent a 75% chance of winning, 25% chance of losing, and 0% chance of d=
rawing. On the other extreme it could represent a 50% chance of winning, 0%=
 chance of losing, and 50% chance of drawing. The probability of drawing, a=
s opposed to having a decisive result, is not specified in the Elo system. =
Instead, a draw is considered half a win and half a loss. In practice, sinc=
e the true strength of each player is unknown, the expected scores are calc=
ulated using the player's current ratings as follows.
</p><p>If player&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">A</span> has a rating of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-elem=
ent-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" sty=
