\tfrac {1}{2}}K\;}"></span> points each.
</p><p>
Note that while two wins, two losses, and one draw may seem like a par scor=
e, it is worse than expected for player&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> because their opponents were lower rat=
ed on average. Therefore, player&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">A</span> is slightly penalized. If player&nbsp;<span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> had scored two =
wins, one loss, and two draws, for a total score of three points, that woul=
d have been slightly better than expected, and the player's new rating woul=
d have been <span class=3D"texhtml">[1613 + 32=C2=B7(3 =E2=88=92 2.88)] =3D=
 1617</span>.</p></blockquote>
<p>This updating procedure is at the core of the ratings used by <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIDE" title=3D"FIDE">FIDE</a>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Chess_Federation" title=3D"United=
 States Chess Federation">USCF</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Yahoo!_Games" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Yahoo! Games">Yahoo! Games</=
a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Chess_Club" title=
=3D"Internet Chess Club">Internet Chess Club</a> (ICC) and the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_Internet_Chess_Server" title=3D"Free Inte=
rnet Chess Server">Free Internet Chess Server</a> (FICS). However, each org=
anization has taken a different approach to dealing with the uncertainty in=
herent in the ratings, particularly the ratings of newcomers, and to dealin=
g with the problem of ratings inflation/deflation. New players are assigned=
 provisional ratings, which are adjusted more drastically than established =
ratings. The principles used in these rating systems can be used for rating=
 other competitions=E2=80=94for instance, international <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_football" title=3D"Association football">=
football</a> matches. Elo ratings have also been applied to games without t=
he possibility of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Draw_(chess)" ti=
tle=3D"Draw (chess)">draws</a>, and to games in which the result can also h=
ave a quantity (small/big margin) in addition to the quality (win/loss). Se=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_ranks_and_ratings#Elo_ratings=
_as_used_in_Go" title=3D"Go ranks and ratings">Go rating with Elo</a> for m=
ore.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hubbert_curve" title=3D"=
Hubbert curve">Hubbert curve</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Most_accurate_distribution_=
model">Most accurate distribution model</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Most accurate distribution model"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The first mathematical concern addressed by the USCF was the use of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Norm=
al distribution">normal distribution</a>. They found that this did not accu=
rately represent the actual results achieved, particularly by the lower rat=
ed players. Instead they switched to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Logistic_distribution" title=3D"Logistic distribution">logistic distri=
bution</a> model, which the USCF found provided a better fit for the actual=
 results achieved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowra=
p;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed"=
 title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs refere=
nces to reliable sources. (March 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</su=
p> FIDE also uses an approximation to the logistic distribution.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-fiderr2017_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-fiderr2017-15"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Most_accurate_K-factor">Mos=
t accurate K-factor</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Most accurate K-factor"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The second major concern is the correct "<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span>-factor" used. The chess statistician <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Sonas" title=3D"Jeff Sonas">Jef=
f Sonas</a> believes that the original <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-=
math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-=
a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/M=
athML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \;K=3D10\;}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>K</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>10</mn>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \;K=3D10\;}</=
annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7891abaa943f4dcde984442d80ab2cfb3ecb9245" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:8.78ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \;K=
=3D10\;}"></span> value (for players rated above 2400) is inaccurate in Elo=
's work. If the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K=
</span>-factor coefficient is set too large, there will be too much sensiti=
vity to just a few, recent events, in terms of a large number of points exc=
hanged in each game. And if the K-value is too low, the sensitivity will be=
 minimal, and the system will not respond quickly enough to changes in a pl=
ayer's actual level of performance. Elo's original <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span>-factor estimation was made witho=
ut the benefit of huge databases and statistical evidence. Sonas indicates =
that a <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span>-f=
actor of 24 (for players rated above 2400) may be both more accurate as a p=
redictive tool of future performance and be more sensitive to performance.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Certain Internet chess sites seem to avoid a three-level K-factor st=
aggering based on rating range. For example, the ICC seems to adopt a globa=
l <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>K</i> =3D 32</span> except when playing agains=
t provisionally rated players. The USCF (which makes use of a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_distribution" title=3D"Logistic distri=
bution">logistic distribution</a> as opposed to a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal d=
istribution</a>) formerly staggered the K-factor according to three main ra=
ting ranges:
</p>
