<p>The term "inflation", applied to ratings, is meant to suggest that the l=
evel of playing strength demonstrated by the rated player is decreasing ove=
r time; conversely, "deflation" suggests that the level is advancing. For e=
xample, if there is inflation, a modern rating of 2500 means less than a hi=
storical rating of 2500, while the reverse is true if there is deflation. U=
sing ratings to compare players between different eras is made more difficu=
lt when inflation or deflation are present (see also <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_top_chess_players_throughout_history" titl=
e=3D"Comparison of top chess players throughout history">Comparison of top =
chess players throughout history</a>).
</p><p>Analyzing FIDE rating lists over time, Jeff Sonas suggests that infl=
ation may have taken place since about 1985.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sonasinflat=
ion_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_=
rating_system#cite_note-Sonasinflation-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sonas looks at the h=
ighest-rated players, rather than all rated players, and acknowledges that =
the changes in the distribution of ratings could have been caused by an inc=
rease of the standard of play at the highest levels, but looks for other ca=
uses as well.
</p><p>The number of people with ratings over 2700 has increased. Around 19=
79 there was only one active player (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Anatoly_Karpov" title=3D"Anatoly Karpov">Anatoly Karpov</a>) with a rati=
ng this high. In 1992 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viswanathan_=
Anand" title=3D"Viswanathan Anand">Viswanathan Anand</a> was only the 8th p=
layer in chess history to reach the 2700 mark at that point of time.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Viswanathan_Anand_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-Viswanathan_Anand-43"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> This increased to 15 players by 1994. 33 players had a 2700+ rati=
ng in 2009 and 44 as of September 2012. Only 14 players have ever broken a =
rating of 2800.
</p><p>One possible cause for this inflation was the rating floor, which fo=
r a long time was at 2200, and if a player dropped below this they were str=
uck from the rating list. As a consequence, players at a skill level just b=
elow the floor would only be on the rating list if they were overrated, and=
 this would cause them to feed points into the rating pool.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Sonasinflation_42-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-Sonasinflation-42"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>From 1975 to 1985, the average rating of the top 100 was around 2550=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sonasinflation_42-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-Sonasinflation-42">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> This increased to 2644 in July 2000, and to 2703 in July 2012.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Viswanathan_Anand_43-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-Viswanathan_Anand-=
43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>Using a strong <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_engine=
" title=3D"Chess engine">chess engine</a> to evaluate moves played in games=
 between rated players, Regan and Haworth analyze sets of games from FIDE-r=
ated tournaments, and draw the conclusion that there had been little or no =
inflation from 1976 to 2009.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-44"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>In a pure Elo system, each game ends in an equal transaction of rati=
ng points. If the winner gains N rating points, the loser will drop by N ra=
ting points. This prevents points from entering or leaving the system when =
games are played and rated. However, players tend to enter the system as no=
vices with a low rating and retire from the system as experienced players w=
ith a high rating. Therefore, in the long run a system with strictly equal =
transactions tends to result in rating deflation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_syste=
m#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1995, the USCF acknowledged that several young scholastic players=
 were improving faster than the rating system was able to track. As a resul=
t, established players with stable ratings started to lose rating points to=
 the young and underrated players. Several of the older established players=
 were frustrated over what they considered an unfair rating decline, and so=
me even quit chess over it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-glickman_46-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note=
-glickman-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Combating_deflation">Combat=
ing deflation</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Combating deflation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Because of the significant difference in timing of when inflation and de=
flation occur, and in order to combat deflation, most implementations of El=
o ratings have a mechanism for injecting points into the system in order to=
 maintain relative ratings over time. FIDE has two inflationary mechanisms.=
 First, performances below a "ratings floor" are not tracked, so a player w=
ith true skill below the floor can only be unrated or overrated, never corr=
ectly rated. Second, established and higher-rated players have a lower K-fa=
ctor. New players have a <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>K</i> =3D 40</span>, wh=
ich drops to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>K</i> =3D 20</span> after 30 played=
 games, and to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>K</i> =3D 10</span> when the play=
er reaches 2400.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FideRules_31-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-FideRules=
-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
The current system in the United States includes a bonus point scheme which=
 feeds rating points into the system in order to track improving players, a=
nd different K-values for different players.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-glickman_46=
-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating=
_system#cite_note-glickman-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some methods, used in Norway for=
 example, differentiate between juniors and seniors, and use a larger K-fac=
tor for the young players, even boosting the rating progress by 100% for wh=
en they score well above their predicted performance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_s=
ystem#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Rating floors in the United States work by guaranteeing that a playe=
r will never drop below a certain limit. This also combats deflation, but t=
he chairman of the USCF Ratings Committee has been critical of this method =
because it does not feed the extra points to the improving players. A possi=
ble motive for these rating floors is to combat sandbagging, i.e., delibera=
te lowering of ratings to be eligible for lower rating class sections and p=
rizes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-glickman_46-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-glickman-46"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ratings_of_computers">Ratin=
gs of computers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Ratings of computers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human%E2%80%93computer_chess_ma=
tches" title=3D"Human=E2=80=93computer chess matches">Human=E2=80=93compute=
r chess matches</a> between 1997 (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Deep_Blue_versus_Garry_Kasparov" title=3D"Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov">=
Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov</a>) and 2006 demonstrated that <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_computers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Chess computers">chess computers</a> are capable of defeating even the =
strongest human players. However, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Chess_engine" title=3D"Chess engine">chess engine</a> ratings are difficult=
 to quantify, due to variable factors such as the time control and the hard=
ware the program runs on, and also the fact that chess is not a fair game. =
The existence and magnitude of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/First-move_advantage_in_chess" title=3D"First-move advantage in chess">fir=
st-move advantage in chess</a> becomes very important at the computer level=
. Beyond some skill threshold, an engine with White should be able to force=
 a draw on demand from the starting position even against perfect play, sim=
ply because White begins with too big an advantage to lose compared to the =
small magnitude of the errors it is likely to make. Consequently, such an e=
ngine is more or less guaranteed to score at least 25% even against perfect=
 play. Differences in skill beyond a certain point could only be picked up =
if one does not begin from the usual starting position, but instead chooses=
 a starting position that is only barely not lost for one side. Because of =
these factors, ratings depend on pairings and the openings selected.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Elo_rating_system#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Published engine rating list=
s such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CCRL" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"CCRL">CCRL</a> are based on engine-only games on standard hard=
ware configurations and are not directly comparable to FIDE ratings.
</p><p>For some ratings estimates, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Chess_engine_rating_lists" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chess engine=
 rating lists">Chess engine =C2=A7 Ratings</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use_outside_of_chess">Use o=
utside of chess</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Use outside of chess"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_board_and_card_games"=
>Other board and card games</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DElo_rating_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Other board and card games"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(game)" title=3D"Go =
